		<li id="comment_101712">
			
			<!-- Moderation? -->
			
			<p>@<a href=#comment-101039>Michael</a>: If your new hard drive doesn&#8217;t get you anywhere, and booting into Disk Mode doesn&#8217;t help, certainly your old hard drive should bring it back to its default state.  Since that isn&#8217;t working, try re-seating the cable &#8212; often a loose connection is the problem.</p>
<p>@<a href=#comment-101122>Bernie</a>: I have to assume that unless the power requirements are less for the newer drives (the specs should be listed in the white papers from Toshiba), they won&#8217;t work.</p>
<p>@<a href=#comment-101184>WoofWoof</a>: That is simply untrue.  I&#8217;ve replaced and upgraded dozens of 4G iPod hard drives and never once lost FireWire capabilities.  The 4G iPods are a rock-solid bunch with plenty of room to grow.</p>
			
			<div class="meta">
				<div class="left">
