		<li id="comment_107555">
			
			<!-- Moderation? -->
			
			<p>There&#8217;s always a possibility that such a restriction exists, but I&#8217;ve never run into such a thing.  Usually, OEM parts suppliers like to make as few changes as possible to get the product to the engineering guys, which means &#8212; more than likely &#8212; Toshiba simply slapped an Apple logo on the drive&#8217;s sticker and left it at that.  The iPod firmware shouldn&#8217;t be able to tell the difference between a stock Toshiba drive and an &#8220;Apple+Toshiba&#8221; drive.</p>
			
			<div class="meta">
				<div class="left">
					<strong><cite><a href='http://www.command-tab.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Collin</a></cite></strong>
				</div>
				<div class="right">
					<small>
						<a href="#comment_107555" title="Permanent link to this comment">
							May 16th, 2007 at 6:10 PM						</a> 					</small>
				</div>
