		<li id="comment_145624">
			
			<!-- Moderation? -->
			
			<p>THANK YOU THANK YOU for blogging how to do this. I was able to switch my 5G hard drive this morning. It was hard but I think I did it.</p>
<p>A quick note, I found the explanation of the zif connector on the hard drive is a little confusing. I didn&#8217;t understand where the bar is and ended up just pulling the ribbon cable out. Miracle I didn&#8217;t break it. </p>
<p>There is a little bar (black on the toshiba drives) on the drive&#8217;s connector, where the pins are. This clamps the pins down. If you flip this up 90 degrees the ribbon cable should slide out w/ a very gentle pull. When putting it back, make sure the bar is up, and slide it back in gently. Then clamp the bar back down to secure the pin connection. If you&#8217;re using forceps or an IC tool be careful where on the ribbon you clamp, so that you don&#8217;t damage the electrical traces on the cable.</p>
			
			<div class="meta">
				<div class="left">
					<strong><cite>Subtropical_305</cite></strong>
				</div>
				<div class="right">
					<small>
						<a href="#comment_145624" title="Permanent link to this comment">
							January 17th, 2009 at 1:53 PM						</a> 					</small>
				</div>
				<div class="clear"></div>
			</div>

